          <div class="methodology-grid">
            <div class="methodology-card">
              <h3>Monthly calculation order</h3>
              <p>The synthetic one-time shock is applied before the first period's return, distributions, and contribution routing. Each month then starts with beginning gross market value. Pillar distributions are calculated, the selected smooth NAV/price return is applied, A/C distributions are reinvested, and any eligible external contribution is added to market value. B/D cash pays the inflated expense target, margin principal repair reduces debt, and interest is estimated separately from beginning debt.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="methodology-card">
              <h3>Assumptions, not predictions</h3>
              <p>Returns, yields, dividend growth, inflation, and distribution behavior are smooth user-selected assumptions, not forecasts. The immediate synthetic market shock is a separate one-time assumption rather than part of the smooth annual NAV/price return. The immediate distribution cut is applied before ongoing annual dividend growth. Actual markets and fund distributions can change unevenly or abruptly.</p>
            </div>
